posts.cooked:
My 10 minutes in hot takes:  
Wow! I did not expect more than 2 voters per minute! Glad to see more teams made changes than not; definitely not what I saw at Magnolia and Bayou. I was surprised to see 3-piece bumpers at about 25%. Maybe influenced by 456, among those with more than 1 piece, I saw mostly 4-piece all-lapped bumpers, no 3s, and the 2s were L‚Äôs with two wrap arounds and two laps. I saw MANY more robots at Magnolia and Bayou with bumper backings taller than 8‚Äù. Most of those taller backings were bits of polycarb designed to deflect CAGEs or game pieces that covered about 20% to 50% of the perimeter, but they were by rules part of the BUMPERS.

posts.cooked: I meant for the fabric to wrap around the corner. Examine Figure 8-7 in the rules, particularly the top row of legal setups. Overlap refers to layers or two of fabric being visible from the backer in the corner when wrapping; simply put, wrapping ensures the fabric stays hidden.

Hi y‚Äôall!

My name is Marco, and I‚Äôm from Team 4146, the Sabercats.

I wanted to write a quick post to help anyone still struggling with their bumpers, especially with this year‚Äôs rule changes. We‚Äôve learned a lot during our build process, so here‚Äôs a breakdown of what we‚Äôve done in the past, what‚Äôs changed, and how we adapted.

**Past Bumper Design and Assembly**

In previous years, we used a 3/4-inch-thick wood backing for our bumpers. Each board was cut ¬Ω-inch longer than the robot's sides and connected at the corners with metal brackets. We mounted them using metal L-brackets inside the frame and wing nuts on both sides.

**2025 Rule Changes + Our New Bumper Design**

This year‚Äôs changes gave teams more freedom with bumper construction, and we took advantage of that. Since our robot is very lightweight, we designed 32-pound bumpers to keep the weight low to the ground, helping prevent tipping.

**New Bumper Design Components**

- **Base boards:** Now ¬æ-inch thick and 8 inches tall.
- **Corners:** Reinforced with 7.5-inch steel L-brackets.
- **Height:** The increased height protects both the bot and the Kraken swerve drives, shielding them from swing cages and potential damage.

**Creative Interior Foam Design**

To create the new design, we started with foam floor mats, cutting them into 3-inch-wide strips stacked 16 layers high. We alternated the corner joints for strength and used cement glue between each layer, allowing them to cure for 24 hours. Once dry, we taped the boards to the foam and sanded the edges for smooth alignment.

**Final Steps**

After reinforcing the interior with foam, we wrapped the bumpers in AndyMark bumper fabric and staples everything down. For more details, check out our video link below or stop by our team at Worlds in the Archimedes division in Scottsdale, AZ. You can email us at team@sabercatrobotics.com for more information.

Good luck, and see you on the field!
